<div class='description narrow'>
<p><p>The American Expatriation &amp; Citizenship Renunciation Guide
<br />How to Divorce the U.S. Government
<br /> 
<br />(Or Any Other Big Brother Nation)</p>

<p>Greetings to anyone who has ever considered escaping from America! I'm writing to you as a former U.S. citizen, born and raised in America. Since the 70’s I have lived (for over 30 years) in other countries. As a youngster I pledged allegiance to the flag every morning at school. Then I grew up and voted in elections. And I paid my taxes. I was what the government would consider a model citizen-asset: I contributed revenue and didn’t complain or dissent. I have a lot of kids and had a lot of wives (one at a time usually).</p>

<p>A dwindling number of my friends and relatives still live in America. I used to go back to visit them. But those visits have become less &amp; less as more &amp; more of them join me abroad. I still consider myself to be “American”, even though I am no longer bound to the U.S. government.</p>

<p>Why did I become an expat and eventually opt out of being a U.S. citizen? I realized a person's family and cultural roots are not the same thing as affiliation with a political entity. My citizenship was an accident of birth. I was pledging allegiance to the government before I even knew what the phrase meant. When I decided I no longer wanted to be a subject of the U.S., I exercised my right to expatriate and moved to Paris.</p>

<p>My ties to the government are what I severed, not my American roots or my relationships with   friends or family I still have in America.</p>

<p>Let's be clear on one thing. I am not advising anyone to renounce his or her citizenship. Usually it is a bad idea to burn your bridges. But good information is hard to find, and in some cases, renunciation may be a sensible option.  </p></p>
